PART 7: ASSUMPTIONS & LIMITATIONS

CRITICAL ASSUMPTIONS:

1. Baseline costs are accurately assessed (recommend independent audit)

2. Improvement rates are conservative (better to under-promise, over-deliver)

3. Community participation remains consistent (partnerships sustained)

4. Environmental measurements are rigorous (third-party verification)

5. Neurochemical proxies are valid (validated instruments used)

6. Generational projections assume continued practice (not guaranteed)

7. External factors remain relatively stable (no major economic/environmental shocks)

---

LIMITATIONS:

1. Cannot quantify all benefits (consciousness evolution, spiritual fulfillment, existential meaning)

2. Generational projections are extrapolations (actual outcomes may vary)

3. Systemic ripple factors are estimates (actual replication rates unknown)

4. Human value monetization is contextual (dollar per point varies by region)

5. Long-term projections (75 years) have high uncertainty (use as directional, not precise)

---

RECOMMENDATIONS FOR CREDIBILITY:

1. Use conservative estimates throughout (err on side of caution)

2. Document all assumptions explicitly (transparency builds trust)

3. Third-party verification of environmental data (independent audits)

4. Validated instruments for neurochemical proxies (published scales)

5. Regular reporting with actual outcomes vs. projections (build track record)

6. Adaptive management (adjust projections based on real data)

